European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, Nazi occupation.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the middle of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations in Europe for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors, combined together, have convinced me that Europe represents a single political unit, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever  one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated  is a mistake.
It is as if one part of a room could be heated while the other part remained cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event elicits an echo throughout Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to take in the new post-communist democracies  which is in Europe's interest , a number of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and within the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must promote community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
Denn a living society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies to become an organic part of a common continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more interconnected they are, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer diverse solidarity tasks to self-managed institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economical it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that the central authorities cannot recognize.
The social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest basis for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy with its neglect of European solidarity, which led to the Munich capitulation.
This experience is still a strong call for vigilance.
The evil must be confronted as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if only governments act.
Denn government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is working intensively on a new concept of its security policy.
It should be characterized by the ability to make decisions quickly and to implement collective decisions swiftly  reforms that were deemed necessary by recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom as well as the interests of pan-European security require interventions beyond the EU's borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action is, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate may not come, even though intervention is in the interest of many people, of all of Europe, indeed of human civilization itself.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared for it, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
But there are still further matters to address in the field of preventive security, but it is also necessary for this security to reflect the values of the expanded civil society in Europe.
Tens of thousands of human lives and an enormous amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of the former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the beginning of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, action was timid.
These failures were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot forever remain dependent on the USA, especially not regarding European issues.
It must be able to reach its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves incapable of reaching agreement on means and ways to protect human rights, not only on its own territory, but also in areas that may one day join it.
Such an EU enlargement is only feasible if it proceeds hand in hand with a determined reform of EU institutions.
I am hopeful that the government conference on institutional reform will put forward practical proposals for advancing the Union.
Aber ich betrachte dies als den Beginn eines Prozesses, der vielleicht Jahrzehnte dauern wird und der von einem dauerhaften Bestreben geleitet werden sollte, die EU-Entscheidungsfindung zu beschleunigen und transparenter zu machen.
Ein mit der institutionellen Reform zusammenhängender Punkt ist die Frage, wie man kleineren Staaten die Gewissheit geben kann, dass sie nicht einfach von den größeren überstimmt werden, und dabei dennoch die Größe der einzelnen Staaten gebührend berücksichtigt.
Eine Möglichkeit besteht in der Einrichtung einer zweiten Kammer des Europäischen Parlaments; die Mitglieder dieser zweiten Kammer werden nicht direkt, sondern von den Parlamenten der Mitgliedsstaaten aus den eigenen Reihen gewählt.
Die erste Kammer der EU  d.h. das gegenwärtige Parlament  würde also die Größe der einzelnen Mitgliedsstaaten widerspiegeln, die zweite Kammer würde, bei gleicher Anzahl von Repräsentanten für jeden Staat, die Gleichheit erhöhen.
Früher oder später werden diese Änderungen erfordern, dass die EU eine klare, verständliche Verfassung besitzt  einen Text, den alle europäischen Kinder lernen könnten.
Such a constitution would need two parts.
Part one would define the rights and duties of both European citizens and the states, the underlying values, and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships with each other.
Such a fundamental law would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal superstate feared by Eurosceptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, to better understand it, to see the significance of the EU for their lives, and, consequently, to identify with it.
